<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between SEER and SEER2?", answer: "SEER is the older Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio test method. SEER2 is the new method effective January 2023, which better reflects real-world conditions using higher external static pressure on the blower. SEER2 ratings are approximately 4-5% lower than the equivalent SEER ratings for the same unit. A 15 SEER unit becomes roughly 14.3 SEER2; a 16 SEER becomes about 15.2 SEER2." },
  { question: "What is EER and how is it different from SEER?", answer: "EER (Energy Efficiency Ratio) is a steady-state measurement at 95 °F outdoor and 80 °F indoor — a single operating point. SEER averages efficiency across a simulated cooling season with varying outdoor temperatures. EER is lower than SEER because the rating conditions are harsher. A 16 SEER unit typically has an EER around 12-13. EER matters most in very hot climates where the AC runs hard continuously." },
  { question: "What is COP?", answer: "Coefficient of Performance is the dimensionless ratio of heat output to electric energy input. A heat pump with COP 4.0 produces 4 BTU of heat for every 1 BTU of electric energy consumed. Divide BTU-based ratings by 3.412 to get COP (SEER / 3.412 ≈ seasonal cooling COP). Electric resistance heat has COP = 1.0 by definition." },
  { question: "How do I compare a heat pump to a gas furnace?", answer: "Convert the heat pump's HSPF to seasonal COP (HSPF / 3.412) and compare to the gas furnace AFUE. A heat pump with HSPF 10 has COP 2.93, meaning it delivers 2.93× the energy it consumes. A 96% AFUE gas furnace delivers 0.96× the energy in the gas it burns. Then multiply by electric/gas cost per BTU to compare operating costs." },
  { question: "What is the minimum SEER2 in my area?", answer: "As of January 2023, the US Department of Energy requires minimum 13.4 SEER2 for split systems in northern regions and 14.3 SEER2 in southern and southwestern regions. Heat pumps must meet 14.3 SEER2 nationwide. These are replacement minimums for new installations — existing equipment is grandfathered." }
]) %>

